00:25:59,804 --> 00:26:02,145
a huge hiring campaign.

482
00:26:02,145 --> 00:26:04,707
Every single one of our studios all over the world

483
00:26:04,707 --> 00:26:05,748
is hiring right now.

484
00:26:05,748 --> 00:26:08,750
So if you would like to get some experience with salary

485
00:26:08,750 --> 00:26:12,813
negotiation, I strongly urge you to check out our hiring booth.

486
00:26:13,837 --> 00:26:20,061
Before I was the creative director at FGAL, I was the game design department lead at Saibo Games,

487
00:26:20,061 --> 00:26:24,644
and I was also one of the lead designers on Plants vs. Zombies 2 at PopCap.

488
00:26:24,644 --> 00:26:30,687
I've been deeply involved in hiring in almost every job I've had over the last seven years,

489
00:26:30,687 --> 00:26:35,210
whether in an independent company or in studios owned by larger companies.

490
00:26:36,325 --> 00:26:42,452
And to my detriment, it took me a while to realize something important, which was the

491
00:26:42,452 --> 00:26:48,980
ways in which I was getting hired were also the ways in which I was hiring other people.

492
00:26:48,980 --> 00:26:53,906
The constraints that I was under as a hiring manager were often the constraints that people

493
00:26:53,906 --> 00:26:55,868
trying to hire me were under as well.

494
00:26:57,325 --> 00:27:02,789
I have friends with stories about how they tried to negotiate salary or benefits or something

495
00:27:02,789 --> 00:27:06,591
else and instead of countering, the company did actually pull their offer.

496
00:27:06,591 --> 00:27:11,835
If this has happened to you nine times out of ten, it's not because you said or did anything

497
00:27:11,835 --> 00:27:12,655
inappropriate.

498
00:27:12,935 --> 00:27:16,277
But sometimes there are just requests that hiring managers can't fulfill.

499
00:27:16,277 --> 00:27:20,440
And if you haven't phrased those requests correctly,

500
00:27:20,440 --> 00:27:24,842
it's easy for a studio to believe that employing you wouldn't work out,

501
00:27:24,842 --> 00:27:28,324
even if you would have actually been fine taking the original offer.

502
00:27:28,324 --> 00:27:31,646
So, if you've ever sat at your computer

503
00:27:31,646 --> 00:27:36,088
staring at an offer letter and wondering what the hiring manager was thinking

504
00:27:36,088 --> 00:27:37,970
when they were drafting its contents,

505
00:27:37,970 --> 00:27:39,290
let me let you in on the secret.

506
00:27:39,779 --> 00:27:43,115
First of all, we really want you to take the job.

507
00:27:43,838 --> 00:27:46,419
Do you know how expensive hiring is?

508
00:27:46,419 --> 00:27:49,539
A studio may be paying internal recruiters,

509
00:27:49,539 --> 00:27:51,860
contracting with external recruiters,

510
00:27:51,860 --> 00:27:54,741
paying to place job ads on job boards,

511
00:27:54,741 --> 00:27:58,782
and a million other small things that all cost money.

512
00:27:58,782 --> 00:28:01,703
Even small studios usually have someone whose job it is

513
00:28:01,703 --> 00:28:04,564
to just go through LinkedIn while they're on the clock.

514
00:28:04,564 --> 00:28:06,784
Sometimes it's an HR representative,

515
00:28:06,784 --> 00:28:09,985
but often it's just the hiring manager themselves

516
00:28:09,985 --> 00:28:12,086
when they get fed up about the role sitting empty.

517
00:28:13,495 --> 00:28:17,418
But there's also the expense of just having the empty desk.

518
00:28:17,418 --> 00:28:21,702
Sure, the company's not paying a salary right then,

519
00:28:21,702 --> 00:28:24,264
but if there's somebody in the office who's given notice,

520
00:28:24,264 --> 00:28:26,286
every day without their replacement

521
00:28:26,286 --> 00:28:27,687
is a day when there's no handover,

522
00:28:27,687 --> 00:28:31,070
when some precious amount of institutional knowledge

523
00:28:31,070 --> 00:28:32,511
is risking getting lost.

524
00:28:33,096 --> 00:28:36,258
Or if there is actually a desk already sitting empty,

525
00:28:36,258 --> 00:28:41,160
that's another day with somebody who has differing skills and responsibilities

526
00:28:41,160 --> 00:28:47,483
having to cover them, adding additional stress and taking away from that person's original workload.

527
00:28:47,483 --> 00:28:51,765
Maybe they can't have anyone cover that role at all, and the role just isn't getting done.

528
00:28:51,765 --> 00:28:54,887
Maybe it's holding up the timeline of a project.

529
00:28:54,887 --> 00:28:57,628
Maybe that means that a publisher is breathing down their neck.

530
00:28:59,624 --> 00:29:05,409
So sure, there might be someone else waiting in the wings to accept if you turn the job down,

531
00:29:05,409 --> 00:29:10,054
but while you're deliberating on whether this job is right for you,

532
00:29:10,054 --> 00:29:13,878
that runner-up may be out interviewing for their dream role.

533
00:29:13,878 --> 00:29:19,604
And regardless, we already decided that person is the runner-up. We want you.

534
00:29:20,924 --> 00:29:25,790
And if there's not a runner-up, that means we have to spend even more on recruitment,

535
00:29:25,790 --> 00:29:31,858
starting over from scratch, pushing the timeline down the road by weeks or months, which is

536
00:29:31,858 --> 00:29:33,701
a pretty shitty worst-case scenario.

537
00:29:35,254 --> 00:29:38,556
We're not trying to insult anyone with a lowball offer.

538
00:29:38,556 --> 00:29:42,178
Nothing about offering you a job is trying to make you feel bad.

539
00:29:42,178 --> 00:29:44,239
We're just crossing our fingers that you take it,

540
00:29:44,239 --> 00:29:48,501
and doing everything in our power to try to make the offer compelling.

541
00:29:48,501 --> 00:29:52,323
We're trying to get to yes with you as quickly and efficiently as possible.

542
00:29:54,242 --> 00:29:57,125
But we're not in control of everything,

543
00:29:57,125 --> 00:29:59,067
especially if you're applying to a studio

544
00:29:59,067 --> 00:30:00,589
owned by a larger company.

545
00:30:00,589 --> 00:30:02,611
There are salary bands in play

546
00:30:02,611 --> 00:30:04,974
that sometimes we just can't go out of.

547
00:30:04,974 --> 00:30:06,836
I know this is a lot of people

548
00:30:06,836 --> 00:30:09,139
trying to get into their first job in the industry,

549
00:30:09,139 --> 00:30:11,622
so quick show of hands, who knows what a salary band is?

550
00:30:13,257 --> 00:30:13,737
OK, great.

551
00:30:13,737 --> 00:30:15,097
I'll do a really quick definition.

552
00:30:15,097 --> 00:30:18,659
Basically, it means that the company as a whole

553
00:30:18,659 --> 00:30:21,200
sets a salary range for each particular title

554
00:30:21,200 --> 00:30:23,181
that the company has.

555
00:30:23,181 --> 00:30:26,983
And they don't allow people to go outside of that band.

556
00:30:26,983 --> 00:30:28,684
Sometimes we can get wiggle room there

557
00:30:28,684 --> 00:30:31,145
by changing the title in order to get a little bit more

558
00:30:31,145 --> 00:30:32,005
salary.

559
00:30:32,005 --> 00:30:35,307
But in order to do that, we have to justify that title

560
00:30:35,307 --> 00:30:36,627
change for the role.

561
00:30:36,627 --> 00:30:38,848
And the parent company may not authorize

562
00:30:38,848 --> 00:30:40,069
changing that resource.

563
00:30:41,620 --> 00:30:46,262
At a previous company, I once had a role sit open for months because the salary band we

564
00:30:46,262 --> 00:30:51,443
were required to stay within wasn't compelling to the people who had the skills that we needed,

565
00:30:51,443 --> 00:30:56,025
and it was difficult to get our parent company to change the role title on offer to something

566
00:30:56,025 --> 00:30:57,045
with a better salary.

567
00:30:58,155 --> 00:31:02,981
Likewise, special requests are often a great way to get value when you can't get more of

568
00:31:02,981 --> 00:31:06,807
a salary, but some requests are harder than others to grant.

569
00:31:06,807 --> 00:31:11,934
Things that are visible to the rest of the studio, like regular work from home days or

570
00:31:11,934 --> 00:31:12,955
extra vacation days.

571
00:31:13,666 --> 00:31:17,249
are often suggestions that are made in articles and that kind of thing.

572
00:31:17,249 --> 00:31:21,712
But unless the office already has a standing work from home policy

573
00:31:21,712 --> 00:31:24,514
or a flexible vacation allowance,

574
00:31:24,514 --> 00:31:27,536
studios can be really concerned that offering special treatment

575
00:31:27,536 --> 00:31:30,658
could set a precedent and annoy veteran employees.

576
00:31:30,658 --> 00:31:34,821
Maybe a company could afford to give you an extra week of vacation time,

577
00:31:34,821 --> 00:31:38,524
but if they have to multiply that by 50 or 100 employees,

578
00:31:38,524 --> 00:31:40,185
that gets hairy real fast.

579
00:31:42,607 --> 00:31:45,569
We also don't want to hire you.

580
00:31:45,569 --> 00:31:47,591
We want to retain you.

581
00:31:47,591 --> 00:31:50,014
If you tell us that it is vitally important

582
00:31:50,014 --> 00:31:51,956
that you make 20% more than we offered you,

583
00:31:51,956 --> 00:31:54,238
and that takes it outside of the salary band,

584
00:31:54,238 --> 00:31:57,701
or that you need to work from home two days a week

585
00:31:57,701 --> 00:31:59,323
in order to be happy and successful,

586
00:31:59,323 --> 00:32:01,465
but the policy is one day a week,

587
00:32:01,465 --> 00:32:04,748
then yeah, we might pull the offer.

588
00:32:04,748 --> 00:32:05,709
Why?

589
00:32:05,709 --> 00:32:06,750
Because we believe you.

590
00:32:08,097 --> 00:32:14,099
If you decide in the moment to settle for a salary 20% less than what you told us you need,

591
00:32:14,099 --> 00:32:19,680
that means your interest is going to be peaked by every single recruiter who contacts you on

592
00:32:19,680 --> 00:32:25,342
LinkedIn. You'll rate your job satisfaction lower on every annual company review.

593
00:32:25,342 --> 00:32:28,403
And you might get raises, and believe me, if you're doing your best,

594
00:32:28,403 --> 00:32:32,324
we will advocate as hard as we can to get you those raises.

595
00:32:32,324 --> 00:32:37,185
But every time we do, we'll both know that you still believe you're worth more than you're

596
00:32:37,185 --> 00:32:37,405
getting.

597
00:32:38,020 --> 00:32:40,603
which means you have a higher likelihood of quitting,

598
00:32:40,603 --> 00:32:43,688
which means that we lose the training and energy put into you,

599
00:32:43,688 --> 00:32:49,115
and we have to go through the expense of hiring all over again.

600
00:32:49,115 --> 00:32:52,880
We want you to be happy right from the jump, and if we think we can't give you

601
00:32:52,880 --> 00:32:55,383
what you need to be happy, there's no moving forward.

602
00:32:56,357 --> 00:32:58,679
I know, this sounds really depressing.

603
00:32:58,679 --> 00:33:02,344
Everyone else is telling you to negotiate and it sounds like I'm just up here giving

604
00:33:02,344 --> 00:33:03,846
you the company line.

605
00:33:03,846 --> 00:33:08,071
But really, I want you to know the lay of the land before we start talking about how

606
00:33:08,071 --> 00:33:11,515
you can make this information work for you.

607
00:33:11,515 --> 00:33:15,600
First of all, there is a salary band, not a salary.

608
00:33:16,279 --> 00:33:20,601
This isn't true for every studio, but if you're applying someplace really large,

609
00:33:20,601 --> 00:33:25,945
or at a company that owns multiple studios, it's almost certainly true in order to keep

610
00:33:25,945 --> 00:33:32,709
things equal and fair. So, when you feel it's appropriate, you can utter these magic words.

611
00:33:32,709 --> 00:33:37,212
I know it's a bit early, but I'm in discussions with a few other studios and I just wanted to

612
00:33:37,212 --> 00:33:41,975
make sure we're aligned. I understand that compensation is more than salary,

613
00:33:41,975 --> 00:33:43,936
but what is your range for this role?

614
00:33:44,590 --> 00:33:48,173
If they ask you what you're currently making, and you're not in California,

615
00:33:48,173 --> 00:33:52,657
say that you're just trying to ensure salary is competitive for the current market.

616
00:33:52,657 --> 00:33:57,261
After all, it's not like they're competing against your old studio to hire you.

617
00:33:57,261 --> 00:34:03,847
There's a chance that when you try to negotiate that first offer you're made,

618
00:34:03,847 --> 00:34:06,670
you may be told that that's the top of their range.

619
00:34:07,486 --> 00:34:08,986
That could be possible.

620
00:34:08,986 --> 00:34:11,847
If you hear that, it's because one of many things

621
00:34:11,847 --> 00:34:13,587
could be going on.

622
00:34:13,587 --> 00:34:16,008
Maybe you made your salary history and expectations clear,

623
00:34:16,008 --> 00:34:19,129
and they knew it would be a stretch to compete if they

624
00:34:19,129 --> 00:34:21,729
didn't start as high as possible.

625
00:34:21,729 --> 00:34:24,190
Maybe you're more qualified than the other applicants,

626
00:34:24,190 --> 00:34:25,890
so they're really afraid of losing you,

627
00:34:25,890 --> 00:34:29,311
so they wanted to come out really strong from the gate.

628
00:34:29,311 --> 00:34:32,772
Or maybe they're being foolish and risking

629
00:34:32,772 --> 00:34:35,793
a relationship that should be built on trust by lying to you.

630
00:34:37,168 --> 00:34:44,734
Look, most of the time, there is absolutely no reason for the first offer to be the best offer.

631
00:34:44,734 --> 00:34:47,856
Not just because it's not financially responsible for the studio,

632
00:34:47,856 --> 00:34:53,200
but it also could mean that there's less room for raises early on in your tenure,

633
00:34:53,200 --> 00:34:56,543
because you're already at the top of that salary band.

634
00:34:56,543 --> 00:34:59,545
But the main issue is this.

635
00:34:59,545 --> 00:35:04,108
We live in a society where most people expect to be able to negotiate their salary offer.

636
00:35:04,493 --> 00:35:11,417
Consistently offering the top of your range is a great way to lose candidates who assume you're just being stingy.

637
00:35:11,417 --> 00:35:15,900
Recruiters in HR read the exact same hiring advice as everyone else.

638
00:35:15,900 --> 00:35:23,044
If the candidate is never supposed to accept the first offer, the company has to leave some breathing room.

639
00:35:23,044 --> 00:35:25,726
How much breathing room?

640
00:35:25,726 --> 00:35:32,790
Not a ton, but usually enough to make a difference. If you're talking about a salaried role, I would not go more than 5k.

641
00:35:33,295 --> 00:35:38,220
The tricky part is estimating where you are inside of a salary band.

642
00:35:38,220 --> 00:35:43,284
It's rare that a company would automatically offer at the lowest part of their range, but

643
00:35:43,284 --> 00:35:47,608
it's also really rare that they would agree to offer a candidate that they did offer at

644
00:35:47,608 --> 00:35:51,651
the lowest part of their range, the highest possible part of the salary band.

645
00:35:51,651 --> 00:35:57,516
You might be able to negotiate more in special circumstances, but if you're trying to be

646
00:35:57,516 --> 00:35:59,158
safe, I would stick around 5K.

647
00:36:01,713 --> 00:36:04,996
Also, if you can't get the salary you're looking for,

648
00:36:04,996 --> 00:36:09,639
negotiate benefits that are unique to your specific situation.

649
00:36:09,639 --> 00:36:12,201
If studios are rightly concerned with equality,

650
00:36:12,201 --> 00:36:15,104
it may be difficult to get more of the things

651
00:36:15,104 --> 00:36:18,427
that are standardized throughout all employees.

652
00:36:18,427 --> 00:36:20,228
But when you're starting at a new company,

653
00:36:20,228 --> 00:36:23,811
that's a great time to bring up ideas for unique benefits

654
00:36:23,811 --> 00:36:26,833
that wouldn't necessarily apply to everyone in the first place.

655
00:36:27,980 --> 00:36:32,405
If you're relocating for a job, it could be much easier to negotiate a higher relocation

656
00:36:32,405 --> 00:36:34,647
package than a higher salary.

657
00:36:34,647 --> 00:36:40,334
When I first got my first job in Europe, I was terrified of getting stranded because

658
00:36:40,334 --> 00:36:45,900
international relocation is a nightmare and I was uprooting my entire family just to take

659
00:36:45,900 --> 00:36:47,021
a chance on this company.

660
00:36:47,582 --> 00:36:53,144
I used my unique situation to negotiate a clause in my contract where if I left the

661
00:36:53,144 --> 00:36:59,486
company for any reason in the first 12 months, they would then relocate me back to the city

662
00:36:59,486 --> 00:37:03,808
of my choice in the United States, all expenses paid.

663
00:37:03,808 --> 00:37:09,790
So when I lost my job after 11 months, knowing that I could get my family home if I didn't

664
00:37:09,790 --> 00:37:13,051
find a job that worked for me in Europe was a massive relief.

665
00:37:14,845 --> 00:37:17,747
I also have friends who have negotiated successfully

666
00:37:17,747 --> 00:37:20,168
for personal development days, basically

667
00:37:20,168 --> 00:37:22,350
being able to go to conferences on their own dime

668
00:37:22,350 --> 00:37:24,271
without taking vacation time to go.

669
00:37:24,271 --> 00:37:26,393
This is a great tactic to take if you're

670
00:37:26,393 --> 00:37:28,754
new to the game industry, because you can really

671
00:37:28,754 --> 00:37:33,017
spin that as wanting to get even more experience and even

672
00:37:33,017 --> 00:37:35,659
more knowledge as quickly as possible.

673
00:37:35,659 --> 00:37:38,441
Fewer friends have been able to get guaranteed paid access

674
00:37:38,441 --> 00:37:40,343
to certain conferences every year,

675
00:37:40,343 --> 00:37:42,084
but it never hurts to ask if you can make

676
00:37:42,084 --> 00:37:43,305
a really compelling argument.

677
00:37:44,018 --> 00:37:47,141
Basically, when you're asking for these unique perks,

678
00:37:47,141 --> 00:37:51,184
imagine a co-worker who gets paid exactly what you get paid

679
00:37:51,184 --> 00:37:53,626
coming to HR and saying,

680
00:37:53,626 --> 00:37:57,068
why does this person get so much more than I get

681
00:37:57,068 --> 00:37:59,970
when I've been with the company so much longer?

682
00:37:59,970 --> 00:38:05,895
Give the HR person a really compelling argument to make.

683
00:38:05,895 --> 00:38:09,998
Look, job hunting is basically like online dating.

684
00:38:10,773 --> 00:38:15,476
When you start out, you're doing everything possible on your Tinder or your OkCupid profile

685
00:38:15,476 --> 00:38:17,517
to seem broadly appealing.

686
00:38:17,517 --> 00:38:22,540
But once you're tired and jaded, your profile just becomes a list of shit you're not willing

687
00:38:22,540 --> 00:38:26,923
to put up with any longer in order to weed out people early.

688
00:38:26,923 --> 00:38:30,905
Don't be hostile or aggressive because you might put off people you could click with.

689
00:38:30,905 --> 00:38:33,647
Instead, just be friendly and honest about what you're looking for.

690
00:38:34,950 --> 00:38:40,132
I had a fantastic interview with a company whose work was incredibly exciting to me.

691
00:38:40,132 --> 00:38:46,413
They flew me to a totally different country, put me up in an amazing hotel, took me out

692
00:38:46,413 --> 00:38:51,374
to dinner the night before my interview, and then I spent the entire day of interviews

693
00:38:51,374 --> 00:38:55,855
being really excited and energized by all of the interviews and discussions.

694
00:38:56,475 --> 00:39:03,858
And then in the very last minutes of the very last interview with the head of the company at 6 at 6 p.m

695
00:39:03,858 --> 00:39:07,859
He asked me what my salary expectations were

696
00:39:07,859 --> 00:39:10,760
I said I didn't know what the cost of living was in that country

697
00:39:10,760 --> 00:39:16,062
But I was more than happy to offer my last two salaries for reference

698
00:39:16,062 --> 00:39:22,324
Yeah, a few days later. I got a very lovely email saying that there was no way they could afford me

699
00:39:22,324 --> 00:39:24,825
But if anything changed to please let them know

700
00:39:25,680 --> 00:39:28,261
I'm actually really glad that I had that experience.

701
00:39:28,261 --> 00:39:31,903
I keep in touch with a lot of the people that I met on that interview,

702
00:39:31,903 --> 00:39:33,743
and it was a really lovely trip.

703
00:39:33,743 --> 00:39:37,365
But if either of us had brought up salary earlier in the process,

704
00:39:37,365 --> 00:39:40,846
it would have saved them some money and me some jet lag.

705
00:39:42,171 --> 00:39:45,753
If you know that you have particular needs or expectations,

706
00:39:45,753 --> 00:39:48,575
it's worth figuring out a way to bring those things up

707
00:39:48,575 --> 00:39:51,638
politely and casually early in the process

708
00:39:51,638 --> 00:39:54,139
in order to make sure that you're on the same page.

709
00:39:54,139 --> 00:39:56,321
Otherwise, you could end up on a really long,

710
00:39:56,321 --> 00:39:58,642
awkward first date, I mean interview,

711
00:39:58,642 --> 00:40:03,226
without a way to make an excuse and leave.

712
00:40:03,226 --> 00:40:05,767
In conclusion, it's worth remembering

713
00:40:05,767 --> 00:40:07,609
that all of the advice about acting like

714
00:40:07,609 --> 00:40:08,910
you're on the same team

715
00:40:09,450 --> 00:40:14,614
works because at the end of the day, you really are all on the same team.

716
00:40:14,614 --> 00:40:20,118
